Check out our latest vlog, link in bio :)', 'How was your July?', 'Reunited!', 'The finest pussy I seen all year', "Today is one of the most important days of my life.

1. We spent 10 days shooting and 2 weeks editing around the clock for what I believe to be the best client I ever worked with, producing 2 videos that I have never been prouder to show. Yes, I would say it's the best video I ever made (and I've made A LOT of videos). I edited over 3000+ videos over the last decade.

2. I would like to thank @klooksg for being the coolest client ever for taking the leap of faith with us even though we have no subscribers or followers. It is also the first time in my life as an editor that I had no changes to make.

3. I would like to thank my crew for toughing it out and working around the clock to make this happen. Especially @whitexsmoke for crashing on my sofa and working around the clock with me to deliver this video, and @bombiibii for putting up with my shit and whining and still trying to make the best of shituations

4. I would like to thank my girlfriend, @cherylenechan for taking care of me and making sure I didn't collapse on the table while editing and forgetting to go to the toilet or eat.

5. Last but not least, I would like to thank what little friends and fans I had left for sharing and supporting the video and supporting my comeback. It hasn't been easy, but as I mentioned before, all I ever wanted to do was make good videos with no drama, no shade, no tea, and no politics. That will be the direction of my new channel. We also won't be releasing videos on a schedule because I do wish for work-life balance. 

Let our work speak for us.

Link in bio

@xingweird helped me take this pic', 'Year 3 for me in NUS was an extremely tough time. I was riddled with anxiety, stemming from a failing relationship, worrying about a lack of direction of what I wanted to do (aka quarter-life crisis), felt like an imposter in the course I was in, and academic burnout (Computer Science is tough).

Up till that point I never really associated the idea of mental wellbeing with myself. Me, with mental health issues? No way. Only people that were clinically diagnosed could claim they had those issues. Well, that was what I thought.

Intense worry about the uncertainty of my future, feeling a sense of overwhelm and lack of control in my life due to school, constant fatigue and having trouble concentrating. A feeling of dread when it came to nighttime as I struggled to sleep; my head clogged up with thoughts and worries that plagued me throughout the day. These are all symptoms of general anxiety disorder.

You see my fellow students, you arenâ€™t as alone as you think you are. We are all one and the same in our feelings, even if our problems differ. You may think that the problem of you stressing to get an assignment done on time is inferior to that of someone else going through a heartbreak, thus invalidating your right to be anxious.

But itâ€™s not a competition of who has the biggest problem, where only the ones facing the most have the right to seek help for their mental health. All of us have our own problems. The right to your own feelings lies within yourself. It would be great if we could collectively start to acknowledge our own mental wellbeing, to realise that itâ€™s okay that we might have issues, and also to know that we arenâ€™t alone.

To help with that, NUS is organising K(NO)W Stigma 2022, an event centred around breaking the stigmas around mental wellness. Join them in a panel discussion that would help demystify the topic of mental wellness, as well as create a safe space for more in-depth dialogue surrounding mental health.

For more details, head to the @nus.hwb Instagram or Facebook page, and you can sign-up for the event through the link in my bio.

#NUSAreuOK #NUSKnowStigma2022', "Goodbye Sheares Hall, the place I could call a home for the past academic year.

A lesson I've learned about home: A dream home doesn't have to be a bungalow filled with swimming pools, bowling alleys, and more amenities than one could need. You don't need a penthouse, 10,000 square feet, or a balcony that stretches out far and wide. A home is a lot more than the superficial. It's a place of safety, security, comfort, and peace. A place you go to at the end of an exhausting day and immediately feel relaxed. A place without judgment, and where you can let your mind rest and be at ease. Even if that's a small little room at the corner of NUS.

I'm not someone that has a large amount of attachment to Sheares Hall as compared to some of my other graduating schoolmates. I didn't join many events or CCAs, nor have I really made a lot of friends that would honestly persist past this graduation from the hall. But I would be lying if I said that 3 of the 4 years I've stayed here haven't impacted me in a large way.

There are a few things I would miss. The peaceful and quiet nature of Pasir Panjang. Communal living with the few close friends I've taken away. The subtle chirping of birds nestled on the roof (although I won't miss the bird poop), and the gentle breeze that flows through the corridor of the rooftop floor that I stayed on. The idea of having the beautiful campus of NUS like my own backyard. The low-rise buildings nestled around the area, giving me an unobstructed view of the sky in its entirety. As you can tell, this allowed me to experience some magnificent sunsets over the past 10 months.

But what I will miss the most would be having this space I could call mine, even if it was just for a short 10 months. A place I could feel safe in, a space where I could do anything I wanted. A small little room where I could feel at peace. At home. And if this is a teaser of what owning my own place feels like, consider me motivated in wanting to achieve that sooner rather than later.

Goodbye Sheares. Thank you for the lessons learned, the people I've met, the tranquility you've given me, and the motivation you've sparked inside of me.", 'petition for power pose emoji', "Senior's farewell night in Sheares Hall, time for another WADIO

Thanks Aaron for asking me to show up at your party.', 'Iâ€™ve always said that the world is a different place for the heartbroken. It moves on a different axis, at a different speed. Time skips backwards and forwards fleetingly. The heartbroken might go through thousands of micro-emotions a day trying to figure out how to get through it without picking up the phone to hear that old familiar voice. In the land of heartbreak, moments of strength, independence, and devil-may-care rebellion are intricately woven together with grief, paralyzing vulnerability and hopelessness. Imagining your future might always take you on a detour back to the past. And this is all to say, that the next album Iâ€™ll be releasing is my version of Red.
 
Musically and lyrically, Red resembled a heartbroken person. It was all over the place, a fractured mosaic of feelings that somehow all fit together in the end. Happy, free, confused, lonely, devastated, euphoric, wild, and tortured by memories past. Like trying on pieces of a new life, I went into the studio and experimented with different sounds and collaborators. And Iâ€™m not sure if it was pouring my thoughts into this album, hearing thousands of your voices sing the lyrics back to me in passionate solidarity, or if it was simply time, but something was healed along the way.

Sometimes you need to talk it over (over and over and over) for it to ever really be... over. Like your friend who calls you in the middle of the night going on and on about their ex, I just couldnâ€™t stop writing. This will be the first time you hear all 30 songs that were meant to go on Red. And hey, one of them is even ten minutes long.

Red (Taylorâ€™s Version) will be out November 12.

SlaÃƒÃ…inte!', None, "Also, Iâ€šÃ„Ã´ve just found out that 'Waiting for the Barbariansâ€šÃ„Ã´, made with my dear friends Mark Rylance and Robert Pattinson, is out in the U.K. this week. Hope you guys get a chance to see it.", 'Hello All!
I just wanted to thank you all once again for your constant and loyal support throughout many long and interesting episodes of my life...
I am only here because of you â€šÃ„Ã® and Iâ€šÃ„Ã´m only here for you!!!

JD', 'Two months before the world was subjected to the shocking live coverage of the merciless, bloodthirsty and public daylight murder of JFK in Nov. 1963, Bob Dylan sat down to write a songâ€šÃ„Â¶ He had a particular idea in mind, which he recorded mere weeks before Kennedyâ€šÃ„Ã´s tragic Assassination. Dylan had already achieved stratospheric acclaim from his treasure-producing workmanship and poetic abilities. He had already jacked up the bar of songwriting to an untouchable level. He also became a reluctant prophet, which can be quite an occupational hazardâ€šÃ„Â¶Yet he remained himself while dodging all manner of con artists, bloodsuckers, angles, arrows, ignorance, injustices, and scrutinization of his life. His intentions remained pure. So he sat down and wrote the gold standard of protest songs, the seminal and most significant, mind boggling and staggeringly poetic, prophetic protest song the world will ever know: â€šÃ„ÃºThe Times They Are A-Changinâ€šÃ„Ã´â€šÃ„Ã¹. Dylanâ€šÃ„Ã´s song applies to Covid-19, it also, very strongly applies to the life altering image of George Floyd, forever seared to our brainsâ€šÃ„Â¶ For me, it applies to the moment we are in, it applies to the moment they were in in 1963, it applies to everything before and everything since and everything that will be. 
I chose to perform this song live, for my friend @drbarbarasturm Covid benefit several weeks agoâ€šÃ„Â¶ I didnâ€šÃ„Ã´t really know how to play it, but I figured Iâ€šÃ„Ã´d give it a shot, as it seemed to apply so well. And it applies now, more than ever. It was performed a couple of weeks before our collective paralysis was rendered complete by the images of our fellow human George Floyd being cruelly and brutally tortured to death on live TV.

Let us take a moment to remember the sacrificial hero George Floyd and look with hope towards the changes that his tragic death will cause. And letâ€šÃ„Ã´s salute the reluctant prophet Bob Dylan and the dream of change he inspired then, now, and onwardsâ€šÃ„Â¶ His impact is that of Shakespeare, Marlowe, Hunter Thompson, Marlon Brando, Woody Guthrie, William Blake, Picasso, Bach and Mozart. 
Dylanâ€šÃ„Ã´s song is to be kept near you, AT ALL TIMES!!! All love and respect,
JD', 'As the majority of American people, our global community and our extended family of humans helplessly watched a man die on televisionâ€šÃ„Â¶ I too, was exposed to the atrocity of blatant barbarism, \xa0ruthless cruelty and unmitigated lack of humanity. \xa0A handcuffed man, pleading for his life lay prone with the full weight of a man sworn to defend the peace on his neck. The victim of this heinous act of cowardice, George Floyd, told the officers that he could not breathe. As he called for his dead mother, how could our collective hearts not break as his face was ground and mashed firmly into the pavement by those sworn to protect him, and all of us? Justice, I desperately hope, will address the horror of Officer Chauvinâ€šÃ„Ã´s nonchalance and indifference to his participation in the agony, suffering and ultimately the murder of our fellow traveler George Floyd in a grotesque illustration of the abuse of power!!!
There is no way to make sense of what is senseless. There is no way to restore a life that has been taken. Just as there is no way to un-break a heart that is broken. 
What we can do is make a vow to ourselves that racism and the ignorance inherent in such judgmental ugliness that it gives birth to, is NO LONGER AN OPTION!!! THERE MUST BE A CHANGE!!! DEMAND IT!!!! My dear friend and brother, Killer Mike - (Run The Jewels), is a brilliant musician, artist, activist for social justice and the son of an Atlanta Policeman. He is also, one of the kindest, most caring and loving human beings that Iâ€šÃ„Ã´ve ever had the pleasure and honor to know!!! I beg everyone to listen to the remarks of this true statesman. True statesmen have never been so needed, and theyâ€šÃ„Ã´ve never been in such short supply. 
With All Love, 
JD', 'Itâ€šÃ„Ã´s odd, the things that we once gave such pure, intense focus and devotion to for months on end. Then suddenly the wind shifts and off we go on a new tack. And for far too long, these earlier interests or passions sadly fall by the wayside and recede into the vast recesses of some hoarderâ€šÃ„Ã´s crawlspace in the brain cloaked in heaps of the other things that my skull had no room forâ€šÃ„Â¶until recently. 
I found this painting, which I had started in 2006 â€šÃ„Â¶ for 14 years Iâ€šÃ„Ã´d never touched the painting â€šÃ„Ã¬ the occasional glance, at best. Yet it somehow always lingered in my mind, this piece of unfinished business. 
Even while we are forced to live in the immediate, some strange species of the interrupted passion that has been invested in an object we once focused on awaits our return from far away. I will keep you apprised of the progress! All Love,

#pradabeautypartner", None, "I didnâ€™t actually set out to start making films. Iâ€™d say the real beginning was taking in what I saw going on around me on set, & then starting to learn how to apply it in other parts of my life. For instance: my Mum nervously would be getting ready for her job interviews, & knowing I knew how to apply makeup after so many hours of watching other people do it in the makeup chair, we made it our ritual that I would do her face before any of her important occasions. 
Then filmmaking itself started by making love letters to my friends. Whether it was styling them, or producing photoshoots for their websites or headshots for their businesses - I loved helping out. Selfishly sometimes I also did it because I just wanted them to see all the beauty I saw in them that they never seemed to get. 
Then over time I started assisting a friend running sound on set. Then, very slowly I started working behind the camera (It hurt my back so much at first ğŸ˜‚). Then I got involved in editing. Now here I am, sharing my first go at directing something. 
I couldnâ€™t have done it without the friends I could be vulnerable enough with to show that I didnâ€™t know what I was doing & to ask for help from every step of the way. To these people (you know who you are) you have literally made a mark on my life & I hope I always get to make things WITH you. Thanks for believing in me. 
@emma_webstah this is my love letter to you. As a woman I always found the idea of living alone terrifyingâ€¦ & when you told me you had been living in the garage above your studio to dedicate yourself to what you really wanted to do despite everyoneâ€™s â€œgood and well intentioned adviceâ€ - was when I knew I wanted to make my first tiny film about you. I just instantly wanted to try & capture who you were & the importance of your work. That's what feels so beautiful about directing to me - you get to fall in love!
Thanks for being so cool Emma. Your work, writing & being inspires me so much. I feel so grateful to have friends like you that I just hope I can keep up with courage-wise. Thanks for being as excited as I was about cookie dough for lunch on the shoot day. And you rock that jumpsuit. E

Not many people know what autism is, or what this entails, but to those who care, thank you.

HH (my brother) was diagnosed with autism at age 2. This was a huge blow to my family. My parents questioned: Why HH of all people? Why us? This is the case for most families whose kids are diagnosed with autism. 

Given that Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) was not well known 21 years ago as it is today, we worried about my brotherâ€™s development and ability to integrate into society. A society that wasnâ€™t forgiving, or accepting to those who did not seem â€œnormalâ€ ( for a lack of a better word ). Everyday, we worried about how HH was going to go to school; make friends; get a job; talk to people; be self sufficient: and the list goes on. The worries were endless. How could we cope with having a family member with ASD, when we ourselves didnâ€™t even know what ASD was? So, what is ASD?

ASD is a developmental disability that affects 1 in 150 children in ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬, and it is generally seen as a different way of thinking. People with Autism often have problems with emotional, social and communication skills- which is why many people think of them as â€œweirdâ€, â€œlonerâ€, â€œeccentricâ€. 

But people with autism should not be defined solely by how they communicate, feel, or act. They just operate a little differently, and different is not necessarily bad. Different can be good. But not everyone thinks that way! And that begets the question: how can I be more accepting of someone who has autism? 

I donâ€™t think there is a right answer to this. You can find a way to do so that suits you! It will definitely not be easy, but please remember to be respectful, and get over prejudice & bias that you may have. It is not everyday you may meet someone with autism, but when you do, be kind. 

It has taken me & my family years, to learn how to cope and function with HH. The journey was difficult, and I do not think it will be easy for years to come. But I am grateful for everything HH has taught us- to be kind, patient, and loving.

today (yesterday) also marks just over a month following the death of a dude who was quintessential to this space.

no amount of consolation, catharsis, coping, vice, distraction, art, sappy songs, poetry, memorial, or pretty quotes about death can ever erase the tragedy and injustice of the loss of the boy with the kindest heart and the kindest smile, who deserved so much better from the world and the people in it. 

the essence of the surreal is something familiar in an unfamiliar context. it was beyond surreal to see a familiar bodyâ€” one we know, weâ€™ve touched, weâ€™ve seen move, we loveâ€” lying in a casket wearing unfamiliar clothes (a suit he would have protested), with an unfamiliar hairstyle (he also wouldâ€™ve protested), and a very unfamiliar wound just above the ear. a wound I canâ€™t get out of my head. 

there is something so surreal about loving someone that does not exist (particularly when they existed just a few moments ago).

there is something so fundamentally wrong with sending a friendâ€™s body into a furnace to burn. 

and now I realise how closely tied we are to spaces, whatever those spaces may be. because as time goes by, finnâ€™s absence from all these spacesâ€” figuratively (our group) and literally (this studio)â€” becomes increasingly clear and increasingly painful.

there is something so wrong with his absence from this world. and there is something so irreconcilable about his non-existence.

but as I grieve his death (and mourn a future that never will be), I also know I have no choice but to simultaneously celebrate his life, particularly on a day like today. and so we try and drink to him and remember good times, his laugh, his person, and his friendship. we pour whiskey at his memorial, and we keep a space open for him. we buy an extra beer. we remember what a fucking good person he was, and we try to let that goodness live through us. it doesnâ€™t bring him back and nothing can ever be the same, but itâ€™s the most we can do to preserve him.

This post will highlight how I love to be underwater and how the quietness and stillness underwater help me achieve my zen mode and reconnect with what I truly love about the sport.

Takagi Ramen stands by Joseph Schooling. Many of us make mistakes. Not all of us own up and face the consequences with courage. True to the bravery of an Olympic Champion, Joseph owned up to using cannabis in the past despite there not being any evidence against him - his urine tested negative for cannabis. 

How many of us are brave enough to admit to something if there is a high chance that we can get away with it?

Itâ€™s very common for people to smoke cannabis overseas, athlete or not. Itâ€™s almost as common as beer. Elite athletes have enjoyed cannabis while enjoying success in their sports careers - Michael Phelps and Diego Maradona are prime examples that you can be at the top of the world and have a little fun as well.

Smoking cannabis will not affect Joâ€™s career. But the outsized overreactions by our society could really affect his mental health. We hope that as Singaporeans, we can handle the situation sensibly, and support our champion as he picks himself up.

For at Takagi Ramen, we have always believed in second chances.

Reminder - Donâ€™t smoke cannabis in Singapore! Drugs is not good for you! If you want to have fun, come to our Marine Parade outlet. We serve alcohol at supermarket prices 24/7 but please take everything in moderation, alochol can be very addictive too!

#supportlocalatheletes #secondchances #takagiramen', 'Key points:

3) The use of marijuana in no way provided Jo with an illegal performance enhancing advantage. I also feel this should be emphasised by the media.

On a macro level, Singapore just needs to grow up. Anyone whoâ€™s been outside this little island would know we are a laughing stock to the world because of some of these laws. This is also where I met @vincentwqh in person finally - big fan of his acting work after growing up watching Heartlanders!', "Fantastic sportsmanship on display over this weekend's @pocarisg 2.4km Elite Selection Trials!

It was a very close race as a long train of runners approached the halfway point of the race. Nick Impey (@nick_impey) of Britain accidentally tripped Singapore's Ethan Yan (@ethanyan01) after running too close behind, resulting in Ethan losing his balance and falling to the ground.

Nick and the runners behind thankfully managed to hurdle over Ethan and avoid further accidents, but Ethan, a favourite to win the race, was in dead last and way off the lead by this point.

As seen in the video, Nick not only looked back to check if Ethan was ok, but came to a complete stop, turned around and encouraged Ethan to get back on his feet and into the race. Nick even voluntarily dropped into last place and encouraged Ethan from behind. Dropping back to help Ethan easily cost Nick about 5 seconds plus all his momentum.

Nick eventually overtook every runner except one to finish in second place (7min 13sec), just 1 second behind the winner, Shaun Goh. It would be fair to say that Nick sacrificed his chance at winning in the name of sportsmanship.

Ethan also displayed good fighting spirit to finish the race, running fast enough (7:17) to qualify for the elite race on August 20 - It promises to be a good race with record holder Jeevaneesh (@gunnerjee) and myself. He has also graciously praised Nick for his act of sportsmanship on Instagram.

In a day and age where winning is often prioritised over values, Nick's sportsmanship deserves to be celebrated and recognised, as does Ethan's fighting spirit. Do help share this video and help make the world a better place through sports!

These days, Iâ€™m a convert and finally understand what everyone means when they say that sleepâ€™s the best form of recovery. Iâ€™m making a conscious effort to go to bed earlier and waking up to my Polar Grit X Pro telling me that Iâ€™ve had a â€œvery goodâ€ night recharge gives me a good idea of how hard I can push for my training - all about listening to the body!

Info - the Polar Nightly Recharge is Polar's version of sleep tracking which shows how well one has slept and recovered during the night.

Sleep Charge is relatively straightforward, measuring the amount and quality of sleep each night. Itâ€™s a classic sleep metric, looking at the hours of rest and sleep cycles, then comparing them to the previous 28 days to see how well one has rested. 

Autonomic Nervous System Charge measures how well the autonomic nervous system calmed down during the first hours of sleep compared to the usual level over the previous 28 days.

The combination of these two scores makes Polarâ€™s Nightly Recharge very comprehensive. Think of them as a sleep quantity and a sleep quality measurement.

From the moment you hold your baby in your arms,
you will never be the same.
You might long for the person you were before,
When you have freedom and time,
And nothing in particular to worry about.

You will know tiredness like you never knew it before,
And days will run into days that are exactly the same,
Full of feedings and burping,
Nappy changes and crying,
Whining and fighting,
Naps or a lack of naps,
It might seem like a never-ending cycle.

But donâ€™t forget â€¦
There is a last time for everything.
There will come a time when you will feed your baby for the very last time.
They will fall asleep on you after a long day
And it will be the last time you ever hold your sleeping child.

One day you will carry them on your hip then set them down,
And never pick them up that way again.
You will scrub their hair in the bath one night
And from that day on they will want to bathe alone.
They will hold your hand to cross the road,
Then never reach for it again.
They will creep into your room at midnight for cuddles,
And it will be the last night you ever wake to this.

One afternoon you will sing â€œthe wheels on the busâ€ and do all the actions,
Then never sing them that song again.
They will kiss you goodbye at the school gate,
The next day they will ask to walk to the gate alone.
You will read a final bedtime story and wipe your last dirty face.
They will run to you with arms raised for the very last time.

The thing is, you wonâ€™t even know itâ€™s the last time
Until there are no more times.
And even then, it will take you a while to realize.

So while you are living in these times,
remember there are only so many of them
and when they are gone, you will yearn for just one more day of them.
For one last time.

â€“Joanthan Fanningâ€“

Living, loving and cherishing these times of â€œMama, we havenâ€™t taken our wefie todayâ€ before the â€˜last timeâ€™ unexpectedly creeps up on me ğŸ¥².

#inspire', "Dare to BeWhen a new day begins, dare to smile gratefully. When there is darkness, dare to be the first to shine a light. When there is injustice, dare to be the first to condemn it. When something seems difficult, dare to do it anyway. When life seems to beat you down, dare to fight back. When there seems to be no hope, dare to find some. When you're feeling tired, dare to keep going. When times are tough, dare to be tougher. When love hurts you, dare to love again. When someone is hurting, dare to help them heal. When another is lost, dare to help them find the way. When a friend falls, dare to be the first to extend a hand. When you cross paths with another, dare to make them smile. When you feel great, dare to help someone else feel great too. When the day has ended, dare to feel as you've done your best. Dare to be the best you can. At all times, Dare to be!
~Steve Maraboli

No regrets, folks. Auntie happily served the waffles to me in brown open-top paper boxes, lovingly sliced into half. - Heat up some cooking oil & add minced garlic & fry for awhile 
- Fry the mushrooms (i used portobello mushrooms cos it has a meatier texture & also enoki) etc. (ie. basically things that take longer to cook like meats)
- Add the kimchi and fry till itâ€™s softer but not totally cooked through
- Add the kimchi juice, followed by the rice & the sauce 
- Mix them well together (i also like to add a little water at this point so it wouldnâ€™t be too dry) 
- Switch off the fire and let it set in the pan for abt a minute
- Finally fry an egg if you would like (you can use sesame oil to fry it for an extra oomph or drizzle sesame oil onto the rice after itâ€™s cooked) 
- Top with roasted sesame seeds & laver to enjoy ğŸ˜‰

*Kimchi fried rice sauce (for 2 servings): 
- 1 tbsp gochujang, 1/2-1 tsp rice vinegar, 2 tbsp kimchi juice (if you donâ€™t have enough can add a little more water & more gochujang instead), 1/2 tsp water

["SPO RECAP, REFLECTIONS. #powerliftingsingapore #powerliftingsg

Finished off SPO with 8/9 successful attempts (3 each for the Squat, Bench & Deadlifts). 

The past months of training was not the smoothest sailing although I had the BEST conditions to have a good prep in the run-up to SPO & although I did win this meet, it was totally under the expectations i've envisioned but my mental game was always up there & i know would never fail me.\xa0 

Starting off with my squat, my last warmup was 200kg before my first attempt of 210, second attempt of 220 & 3rd attempt of 225. Frankly didn't feel good from my last warmup of squat of 200kg and underperformed for this lift as I had squatted more in training. 

Went 3/3 successful attempts with bench at 117.5kg as my first bench attempt, 120 for the second & 122.5 for the 3rd, increasing my bench pr by 2.5kg. 

Went 2/3 successful attempts for deadlifts with a successful 225kg on the first attempt, no lift for my second attempt of 230kg due to a torn callus (2nd photo) which caused my grip to slip before the down command & a successful last attempt of 235kg, also underperformed this lift as I've deadlifted more in the gym. 

And failing the 2nd deadlift really caught me off guard as I've done that weight countless times, even so with my 3rd deadlift attempt, but i knew what I had do to & I know if I had to grind my last attempt, that is what I'll do & honestly what I take away from this meet is to roll with the punches when it comes. Severely underperformed this meet but i'll be stronger than ever next year, that I'm extremely sure of. 

Thanks to @marcusdsk , @matthewyapzr & @fatty.traininglog for making me feel like a king, always being served during the meet ğŸ˜‚ 

Finished with a 582.5kg total. 

Upwards from here.

Squat 190/200/213x (Gold)

During my warm ups, squats felt great. First attempt of 190 didn't move too fast but i didn't allow that get into my head. Second attempt of 200kg felt a little slow and i knew if i wanted the Asian Record of 213kg i would have to fight and i know i am always ready for one. During the attempt for the Asian record coming out of the hole it was fast, then i was stuck for a little second, then it moved a little before the bar rolled over my head and did a little gym****ery. I was so so close to getting an AR in my last year as a sub-jr but i failed to. It was not a very good start but i knew i had bench & deadlifts later on and i couldn't let that affect me. Go to the 4th video for my 3rd attempt squat. (Be sure to watch itğŸ˜‚)
-
Bench 100/105/110 (Gold)

Leading up to the comp my bench was complete shit. Every time i bench it always felt hard.Warmups before my first attempt didnt feel light either. I think one of the takeaways is that i'm glad @marcusdsk gave me different bench variations in my programme which helped me to overload and get used to heavy benching. I was very surprised and satisfied with my bench as 110kg was what i could have done with a slingshot only. -

Deadlifts 215/227.5/235x (Gold)

Similar to squat, deadlift warmup didnt feel good. Groove was abit off on that day during warmups. First attempt wasn't as fast as i wanted it to be. Second attempt was better infact. I thought i had the third attempt as it was a conservative 7.5kg jump. It got off the ground, i got stuck a little then it budged then i got stuck again. I held it on for as long as i could but it didnt move. 
Total 537.5 (Gold)

Rating: 10/10", "Matcha mornings has recently been looking super pretty with this easy Strawberry Matcha Latte â¤ï¸

Ingredients: 
- 3 strawberries, diced into small chunks and slightly mashed
- 200ml milk of your choice (I used VitaSoy here) 
- 4 tbs warm water
- 2 tsp matcha powder @naokimatcha 
- Ice

1. Add the strawberries into the cup
2. Dissolve the matcha in 4 tbs warm water and whisk till foamy 
3. Add the milk into your cup
4. Layer the matcha mixture on top

The Superior Blend from Naoki Matcha checks off all the boxes - distinct umami with a hint of bitterness. As a hardcore matcha lover, I thoroughly enjoyed the earthy profile and the vibrant green ğŸ¥ºâ¤ï¸ A huge plus point for me is that it is really easy to dissolve as well!

The tartness of the strawberries surprisingly goes well with the bitterness of the matcha, giving the matcha latte a very refreshing twist. Feel free to add a dollop of honey to sweeten it up! A big thank you to @naokimatcha for sending this over - i'm a huge fan â¤ï¸
